Malnutrition  particularly of the protein calorie type  is prevalent among hospitalized patients 
While anthropometric measurements and laboratory determinations provide objective information about nutritional status  malnutrition can be identified by a skilled physician using clinical judgment 
Malnutrition should be considered in patients who have recently lost a spouse  have had recent weight loss  are institutionalized  or who have chronic lung disease  alcoholism  cancer  or residual manifestations of a stroke 
Protein deficiency is an evident or potential problem in these conditions 
In such cases  assessment of daily protein intake is important 
Although a dietician can be very helpful in determining the precise dietary intakes of various nutrients  a reasonable estimate of protein intake can be made using simple guidelines 
