Supplementation with minerals and trace elements can result in a significant imbalance of nutrients 
Excessive quantities of one substance can antagonize another essential nutrient 
Chronic excessive zinc intake can produce copper deficiency  and high manganese intake impairs absorption of iron 
These are examples of known potentially detrimental effects from high intakes of specific minerals 
It is likely that isolated increased intake of other minerals and trace elements could have adverse effects 
The key here is moderation  and the use of pharmacologic doses of minerals in the absence of demonstrated deficiency should be discouraged 
